In this article, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. emphasizes the importance of ensuring the safety and well-being of all individuals in their homes, schools, workplaces, and communities. He acknowledges the millions of Americans who become victims of crimes each year and the long-term impact it can have on their lives. President Biden discusses his support for the Victims of Crime Act, which created a fund to compensate victims and finance victim assistance services. He also highlights his efforts to address domestic and sexual violence through the reauthorization and strengthening of the Violence Against Women Act (VAWA). President Biden increased funding for VAWA to its highest level to hold offenders accountable and provide trauma-informed care for victims, particularly those from underserved communities. He signed laws to combat hate crimes, including establishing reporting hotlines and making lynching a federal hate crime. President Biden also signed the Bipartisan Safer Communities Act, aimed at reducing gun violence and providing support for survivors of gun violence. He emphasizes the importance of building trust between the public and law enforcement and outlines his Safer America Plan, which includes additional funding for crime prevention and community policing. President Biden encourages Americans to participate in events that raise awareness of victims' rights and services and to support victims in their time of need.